<dl id="n53112d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53112d">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53112d"> 112(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hill / of Tullymongan / m &mdash; tir / muntir ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53112d"><li>FW 99.26 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n53112d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n53112d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53112d">MS BL 47476a-202</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:425 <a name="dd10" href="../../ff/fdra/dda.htm#dd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd10.htm#n53112d">Draft: I.4&sect;1.10</a>/2.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Shantramon (&lsquo;the old sanctuary&rsquo;) &mdash; a hill situated between Cavan town and Ballyhaise &mdash; was the Place of Inauguration of the chieftains of the O&apos;Reilly sept. The three upright stones employed in this ceremony still stand. At a later date, the site was relocated by the family, at Mongan&apos;s Hill (Irish <i><mark>Tullach Mong&aacute;in</mark></i>), the seat of the principal stronghold of the clan, and the site of the Mint House maintained by them. It was then renamed <i><mark>Muintir</mark> Maolm&oacute;rdha</i> (People of Maolm&oacute;rdha). In 1798 the hill was used as a good spot for a public gibbet and was renamed Gallows Hill.]</font> <small> &ldquo;Irish Family Names: O'Reilly&rdquo;, <a name="WIT21jan33" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WIT21jan33"><cite title="source">Weekly Irish Times</cite></a> (21 January 1933) 4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
